<HEAD>Thieves Steal Three Van Gogh Paintings From Museum, Escape</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Rewrites throughout to specify that stolen ``The Potato
Eaters'' is one of a series, other details. No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OTTERLO, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police searched with tracker dogs and
helicopters but found no clues today to the theft of one of Vincent
van Gogh's ``The Potato Eaters'' and two other works by the Dutch
impressionist master.
   Monday night's burglary at the Kroeller-Mueller National Museum
appears to be Holland's biggest art theft. Also taken were the
19th-century Dutch master's ``Dried Sunflowers'' and ``Weaver's
Interior.''
   Police spokesman Karel van Seventer said the 30-strong task force
this morning abandoned its search of the national park that
surrounds the museum. They have no leads to the thieves' identities
or whereabouts of the oil paintings, he said.
   The burglars smashed an 8-foot square window to get into the
sprawling one-story museum, Seventer said. Two guards on duty in the
museum were not alerted. But the burglars triggered an alarm at Ede
police station, 10 miles away and police surrounded the park near
the West German border within minutes, he said. Nearby border posts
were alerted.
   There was no official estimate of Kroeller-Mueller's ``The Potato
Eaters,'' the second of three versions Van Gogh painted in 1885, and
the other two works, which were finished in 1887. All belong to the
state.
   Experts from Sotheby's and Christie's auction houses in Amsterdam
said the final and most important version of ``The Potato Eaters''
is on display in Amsterdam's Vincent van Gogh National Museum.
   The series marks one of Van Gogh's harshest expressions of
poverty and famine in the southern Netherlands where he was born.
Done in dark pigments, all three paintings show a peasant family
seated around a table and eating potatoes under a hanging lamp, with
suffering evident on their rough faces.
   Van Gogh is the world's best-selling artist. Five of his
paintings were on the list this month of the top 10 prices paid for
paintings at Christie's and Sotheby's. His painting ``Irises''
attracted the highest recorded price paid for a painting _ $53.9
million in 1987.
   ``What on earth can be the reason why to steal these paintings?''
asked Christie's Amsterdam director, Harts Nijstad. ``The answer can
only be, if you ask me, ransom money. Whether the ransom will be ...
moneywise or political is something the future will tell us.''
   Seventer said he believes the theft was committed by more than
one thief because of the size of the paintings.
   ``Wilted Sunflowers'' measures 40 inches by 24 inches, ``The
Potato Eaters'' is 37 by 29 inches and ``Weaver's Interior'' is 34
by 28 inches, according to the Culture Ministry.
   This morning, police began interviewing the museum management and
guards as well as five game keepers living inside the park grounds,
Seventer said.
   The Kroeller-Mueller museum is named for industrialist and art
lover Mrs. H.E.L.J. Kroeller-Mueller, who bequeathed it to the
nation in 1938. It contains 278 Van Gogh paintings, sketches and
etchings.
   Seventer said the Van Goghs, the centerpiece of the collection,
are housed in a separate wing 60 feet from the smashed window.
