<HEAD>Portrait Painted One Month Before Artist's Suicide Goes On Sale</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Also in Monday AMs report.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CATHERINE CROCKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A month before he killed himself, Vincent van
Gogh painted a portrait in blue of his innkeeper's young daughter.
   The girl, Adeline Ravoux, 13, was on the terrace of the cafe in
Auvers, a village outside Paris, when the artist returned from the
fields, his hands pressed to the bullet wound in his stomach. Two
days later, July 29, 1890, van Gogh died. He was 37 years old.
   On Wednesday, ``Portrait of Adeline Ravoux'' will offered for
sale at an auction of impressionist and modern paintings.
Christie's, the auction house, estimates that it will fetch more
than $15 million.
   Experts say interest in the portrait is keen in part because of
the story behind it.
   The adolescent girl who posed for the painting said in an essay
published in 1956 that she considered it ``somewhat of a
disappointment'' at first. But in her later years, Adeline Ravoux
Carrie said she finally came to appreciate its insight into her
character.
   Mrs. Carrie described van Gogh, who lived at her father's inn
during the last 2{ months of his life, as a disciplined artist and
``a soft and calm'' man who always smoked a pipe and enjoyed
playing with her little sister.
   She also recalled the last two days of the artist's life during
which he slowly succumbed to the fatal bullet.
   A doctor came to dress the wound, police officers arrived to
investigate the suicide and the artist's brother Theo arrived
running from the train station, his face ``distorted by grief,''
she wrote.
   The portrait being auctioned Wednesday is one of three versions
van Gogh painted. When last offered for sale, in 1980 at Sotheby's,
it brought $1.98 million from an anonymous buyer.
   Last year, three of van Gogh's paintings fetched record
multimillion- dollar prices that shocked the art world. The artist
sold almost nothing during his lifetime.
   In March 1987, van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' sold for $39.9 million
at Christie's in London to a Japanese firm, Yasuda Fire &amp; Marine
Insurance Co. Three months later, ``The Trinquetaille Bridge'' went
for $20.2 million, also at Christie's in London. It was bought by
an unidentified collector living in Switzerland.
   Then in November, history was made when van Gogh's ``Irises'' _
a richly-colored composition of purple flowers and green leaves set
off by a single white iris _ sold at Sotheby's in New York for
$53.9 million to an anonymous buyer. It was the highest price paid
at auction for any painting.
   John Rewald, the author of ``Post-Impressionism: From van Gogh
to Gauguin,'' has said of ``Irises'': ``If a museum could have one
painting by van Gogh, that's what it should get.''
   Michael Findlay, Christie's senior vice president, said he
didn't think ``Portrait of Adeline Ravoux'' would bring anywhere
near the price paid for ``Irises.''
   The special appeal of the portrait, aside from the painting
itself, is its link to van Gogh's last days, said Findlay.
   In the painting, Adeline, dressed in blue, sits in profile on a
chair. Her blond hair is tied with a blue ribbon, her gaze is
serene, her posture correct and her hands folded demurely in front
of her.
   ``He observed her very deeply, and when he came to paint her, he
painted both the grace and stiff awkwardness of an adolescent
girl,'' Findlay said. He used ``brief flashing strokes'' and
``astonishing'' color; the background is ``almost an electric blue,
a night blue,'' he said.
   Mrs. Carrie, who died in 1965 at age 88, had written: ``I admit
that I was only moderately satisfied with my portrait; it was
somewhat of a disappointment, for I did not find it was true to
life.'' But she also told an interviewer, ``Monsieur Vincent
divined not the young girl I was, but the woman I was to become.''
   Van Gogh gave the first of his three versions of the portrait to
the Ravoux family. More lifelike and detailed than the version up
for auction, it is now in a private collection in Switzerland. A
third version that shows only the face and whose colors are less
brilliant is owned by the Cleveland Museum of Art.
