<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Vincent van Gogh painting owned by Elizabeth
Taylor failed to sell at auction when bidding did not reach the
minimum acceptable price.
   Bidding on ``View of the Asylum and Chapel at St. Remy'' started
at $9.6 million and reached $11.14 million, Christie's said, but
did not achieve the undisclosed reserve price. The auction house
had expected the painting to fetch between $15 million and $19
million.
   Painted in 1889, the work depicts the asylum where Vincent van
Gogh committed himself toward the end of his troubled life. The
actress bought it in 1963 for about $165,000.
   The demand for van Gogh's work has grown since 1987, when
``Sunflowers'' sold for about $40 million. The record price for a
van Gogh was about $57 million, paid for a ``Portrait of Dr.
Gachet'' in May.
   A Christie's spokesman said he believed the current world
economic climate was partly responsible for the failure of Miss
Taylor's painting to reach the minimum price, but added: ``There is
still a strong art market.''
   The painting was shown at the Metropolitan Museum of Art in New
York, as part of a van Gogh exhibition in 1986-87.
   Miss Taylor did not attend the sale.
</TEXT>
