<DATELINE>OTTERLO, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three paintings by Vincent van Gogh,
including his early masterpiece ``The Potato Eaters,'' were stolen
from a national museum on Monday night, police said.
   The art theft appeared to be the biggest in Dutch history.
   The van Goghs were taken from the Kroeller-Mueller National
Museum near the West German border by thieves who apparently gained
entry through a broken window after closing hours, said police
spokeswoman Bep Lijftogt.
   The two other paintings by the 19th-century Dutch impressionist
were ``Dried Sunflowers'' and ``Weaver's Interior,'' she reported.
   Two guards were in the sprawling, single-story museum at the
time, but they noticed nothing amiss, said police spokesman Dirk
Talsma.
   Police immediately sealed off the 25-acre park in which the
museum sits. A helicopter equipped with floodlights and police with
dogs hunted for suspects on the heavily forested grounds.
   They suspended the search at 1 a.m. Tuesday and planned to resume
at daybreak.
   No official valuation of the paintings was available from the
museum, but the director of Christie's auction gallery in Amsterdam
said that if sold on the open market _ not possible for a stolen
work _ ``The Potato Eaters'' could bring as much as van Gogh's
``Sunflowers.''
   That painting brought $39.9 million when auctioned off in London
in March 1987.
   ``The sky's the limit,'' Christie's director Harts Nijstad told
The Associated Press in a telephone interview. ```The Potato Eaters'
is an enormously important painting.''
   ``The Potato Eaters'' in the Kroeller-Mueller museum was the most
complete of several versions of the same subject, according to
Nijstad, who said a less important version sits in the van Gogh
National Museum in Amsterdam.
   No estimate on the value of the other two paintings was
immediately available, but Nijstad said all three were ``frightfully
important.''
   He speculated that the paintings were stolen for ransom, adding,
``Whether the ransom will be money-wise or political is something
the future will tell us.''
   The museum's silent alarm triggered a warning in the local police
station at about 8:45 p.m. (2:45 p.m. EST), and police rushed to the
museum.
   Completed in 1885, ``The Potato Eaters'' is one of van Gogh's
most poignant depictions of poverty and hunger in the Netherlands.
It shows a farm family seated around a table eating potatoes by
lamplight, the hunger evident on their angular faces.
   Five van Gogh works were included in a list published two weeks
ago of the top 10 prices paid for paintings at the world's two major
auction houses, Christie's and Sotheby's. Van Gogh's ``Irises'' was
sold last month for $53.9 million, the highest price paid for any
painting in the world.
   The Kroeller-Mueller has dozens of van Goghs exhibited in a
special wing. The museum and surrounding estate were bequeathed to
the nation in 1938 by art collector Mrs. H.E.L.G. Kroeller-Mueller.
   The theft was the latest in a series of recent burglaries at
Dutch museums.
   In May, thieves broke a window and stole impressionist paintings
by van Gogh, French painter Paul Cezanne and Dutch painter Johan
Jongkind from Amsterdam's Municipal Museum.
   Those paintings were initially valued at up to $50 million, but
art authorities later scaled down the estimated value.
   The paintings were later recovered in a raid on an Amsterdam
hotel spearheaded by an undercover policeman posing as a buyer of
stolen art.
   That theft, mounted through a broken ground-floor window at a
time when no guards were in the Amsterdam museum, prompted calls for
stronger security in the nation's museums.
   The Kroeller-Mueller museum never before had a major theft,
police spokesman Talsma said.
   ``The Potato Eaters'' was painted when van Gogh was living in a
village in southern Holland.
   It is considered his most ambitious work from his Dutch period,
before he moved to France in 1886 and came under the influence of
Impressionism. The painting is done in dark colors in a rough style,
which van Gogh said in a letter to his brother was meant to
illustrate the rough life that the peasants lived.
   Van Gogh's artistic career lasted only 10 years, but during that
time he produced about 850 paintings. About 50 of the paintings are
still in private hands, according to James Roundell, who supervised
the ``Sunflowers'' sale.
   A highly placed source at the Van Gogh Museum said on condition
of anonymity last month that one great fear his museum had was that
the record prices being paid for works by van Gogh would bring ideas
of theft into people's heads.
   Van Gogh sold only one painting during his lifetime.
</TEXT>
