<HEAD>Van Gogh From Met to Be Auctioned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A painting by Vincent van Gogh, loaned to the
Metropolitan Museum of Art in 1984, will leave the museum to be
auctioned for an expected price of up to $50 million, Christie's
auction house says.
   The painting, ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet,'' is from the collection
of Siegfried Kramarsky, a German-born New York banker who died in
1961. It is being sold by a trust created under his will.
   Museum director Philippe de Montebello said he was not surprised
that such a painting was headed for the auction block. ``The
reduced tax advantages to collectors and the increased sale
potential are a combination that is irresistible to collectors and
fatal to museums,'' he said.
   The portrait of Dr. Paul-Ferdinand Gachet was painted six weeks
before van Gogh committed suicide in 1890.
   It will be auctioned May 15, almost precisely 100 years after it
was finished.
   Gachet, a practitioner of homeopathic medicine, was van Gogh's
physician and a friend of Impressionist painters. The doctor, an
artist himself, is shown seated at a table, head in hand, with what
van Gogh called ``the broken-hearted expression of our time.''
   Van Gogh painted a slightly larger version with less detail and
flatter colors. It hangs in the Musee d'Orsay in Paris.
   Another van Gogh, ``Irises,'' was sold at auction in 1987 for
$53.9 million, making it the world's most expensive painting. That
sale, however, was made with a loan from Sotheby's auction house;
when the buyer failed to pay what was owed, the deal fell through.
