<HEAD>Experts Say Painting In Cairo Genuine Van Gogh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIMI MANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CAIRO, Egypt (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A painting of vivid yellow and orange flowers
in a dark vase, hanging on a faded wall of a little-known museum on
the Nile, is an original work by Vincent van Gogh, French experts
say.
   ``It is real, absolutely real, without doubt,'' Francoise Cachin,
director of Paris' Musee d'Orsay, told a news conference Saturday.
   The one-foot-square canvas is among 350 paintings and other art
works at the Mohammed Mahmoud Khalil Museum, which houses the
private collection of an Egyptian senator donated to the state by
his widow in 1960.
   The painting attributed to van Gogh, titled ``Poppies'' by the
museum, is being called ``Flowers'' by the French experts until ``we
can determine exactly what kind of flowers are in the vase,'' said
Cachin.
   In 1967, Egyptian authorities estimated its value at $500,000,
but Cachin didn't give any estimate of how much it might be worth
today.
   A van Gogh painting has commanded the single highest price ever
paid for a painting _ his ``Irises'' sold for almost $53.9 million
in New York in November 1987. Van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' was sold at
Christie's in London in March 1987 for $39.85 million.
   The authenticity of the Cairo painting has been questioned since
it was stolen in 1978 from the domed, arabesque building on an
island on the Nile opposite downtown Cairo. The painting was
recovered at an undisclosed location in Kuwait in 1980.
   ``It is an authenic van Gogh,'' said the curator of the museum's
paintings, Genevieve Lacambre.
   Lacambre, who was curator of 19th-century painting at the Louvre
in Paris for 20 years, studied the canvas attributed to the Dutch
master for three weeks before the results were announced.
   Cachin said the painting resembles a flower scene painted by the
French artist Adolphe Monticelli, whose work deeply affected the
young van Gogh. The Monticelli painting also is part of the Khalil
collection.
   ``It is absolutely correct for the technique of early Van Gogh,''
Cachin said.
   She said the back of the painting has a small, numbered pink
label, ``the kind used by French art dealers.
   ``It would be impossible to imagine someone could copy such a
number,'' said Cachin, who also studied a photograph from the Paris
dealer who sold the painting to Khalil.
   Most of the canvases for which the Dutch-born postimpressionist
is remembered were painted in 29 months of frenzied activity before
his suicide in 1890 at age 37.
   The experts said they believed the Cairo canvas was painted
around 1887.
   Cachin said the painting is in ``a normal condition for a
painting that has been stolen.'' Bernard Malauzat, French Embassy
cultural officer, said the oil had ``small flakes of paint missing.''
   The painting has been ``in some small accident which seems to be
recent, maybe when it was traveling,'' Cachin said. ``It can easily
be restored.''
   The painting has been taken off display and put in storage at the
nearby el-Gezira Museum.
   Authorities have never fully revealed the details of the theft of
the painting. When it was recovered in March 1980, Egypt's
then-interior minister, Nabawi Ismail, said three Egyptians involved
in the theft had been arrested and informed police where the canvas
was left. Authorities never reported whether the thieves were
charged or tried.
   Other works in he Khalil collection, all from the 19th-century
French school, are by Paul Gauguin, Gustave Courbet, Francois
Millet, Claude Monet, Edouard Manet, Auguste Renoir and Auguste
Rodin.
   Malauzat said 90 percent of the the museum's 745 art works _
including 270 sculptures and more than 100 other works _ have been
authenticated.
   ``The majority of paintings are not in bad condition. With proper
expertise and cleaning, they will be back to very bright colors,''
Malauzat said.
 
</TEXT>
