<DATELINE>MALIBU, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``Irises,'' the Vincent van Gogh painting
that sold for a record $53.9 million in 1987, reportedly has been
brought to the J. Paul Getty Museum, which is considering buying it.
   ``The museum isn't commenting,'' Getty spokeswoman Lori Starr
said in response to Wednesday's Los Angeles Times report. Museum
officials would say only that no agreement or purchase had taken
place.
   The owner of the masterpiece, financially troubled Australian
entrepreneur Alan Bond, reportedly has turned down offers of $50
million to $60 million.
   The painting was delivered to the museum, 30 miles west of Los
Angeles, last week, the newspaper said, citing an unidentified
source who saw the painting at the Getty. The pating was last
reported to be at Bond's office in Sydney.
   The New York Times on Thursday quoted museum staff members who
declined to be identified as saying the painting remains at the
museum while negotiations take place involving the Getty, Bond and
Sotheby's auction house.
   Museums often receive artworks before a purchase so curators can
verify the work's authenticity and examine it for possible damage.
   Major acquisitions must be approved by the museum's board of
trustees, several of whom have viewed the painting, the Los Angeles
Times said.
   With a $2.1 billion endowment from the late oil baron J. Paul
Getty, the museum is the world's richest financial institution.
   The 1889 painting, characteristic of van Gogh's bold
postimpressionist style, depicts a field of midnight-blue irises,
except for a single white iris. The landscape is from a corner of
the garden at the asylum of St. Paul de Mausole in St. Remy de
Provence, where the artist committed himself in 1889-90.
   Bond acquired the painting Nov. 11, 1987, at Sotheby's,
reportedly financing the record auction price with a $27 million
loan from the auction house, which accepted the painting as
collateral in an unusual transaction.
   The highly leveraged acquisition, similar to Wall Street
takeover deals of whole corporations during the 1980s, was widely
criticized for inflating prices in the international art market.
   The extraordinary prices paid for art in recent years also have
placed many works beyond the acquisition budgets of art museums.
   Since Bond's financial empire began crumbling under the weight
of more than $5 billion in debt, there has been widespread
speculation among art curators, dealers and collectors about the
fate of ``Irises.''
   The painting was in private European collections until 1947,
when it was purchased for $80,000 by New York philanthropist Joan
Whitney Payson. After a version of van Gogh's ``Sunflowers'' sold
for $39.9 million in 1987, Payson decided to sell ``Irises'' and
use the proceeds to endow a charitable foundation.
