<HL> LEISURE &amp; ARTS:
Van Gogh's Last, Turbulent Work at Met Museum
---
By Jack Flam</HL>
<DD> 12/11/86</DD>
<SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO>
<DATELINE> New York  </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Artists, unlike cowards, die many times after their deaths. 
And the world record for posthumous dying is doubtless held by Vincent van Gogh. 
His suicide in July 1890 has not only been reenacted by Irving Stone and Kirk Douglas, it has also been celebrated in verse and in song, been described and analyzed by historians, physicians, psychologists and philosophers, and been invoked in countless museum galleries and lecture halls. 
Van Gogh's madness and death also provide the point of departure for the Metropolitan Museum of Art's exhibition "Van Gogh at Saint-Remy and Auvers" (on view until March 22). 
This blockbuster chronicles the last 15 months of the Dutch artist's life. 

   Since it is just two years since the opening of the Met's impressive "Van Gogh in Arles" exhibition, the very idea of this kind of sequel poses a question: Can we really bear witness so soon again to poor Vincent's saga, glorious as it may have been? 
The answer, happily, is a resounding yes. 
For what has now become something of a minor industry at the Met has produced yet another major show. 

   Early in May 1890, Vincent van Gogh left Arles for nearby Saint-Remy, where he sought treatment at the local asylum for what was described as "acute mania with hallucinations of sight and hearing which have caused him to mutilate himself by cutting off his right ear." 
During the time that he struggled with himself there, he produced some of his greatest paintings, including some of his most impressive self-portraits and an astonishing series of landscapes. 

   The exhibition, which consists of almost 90 works, opens with paintings and drawings done soon after the artist's arrival at Saint-Remy: studies of the grounds and interior of the asylum. 
The forthright portrayals of the asylum's vestibule and corridors are particularly affecting. 
The detailed renderings of the monastic setting, with its repetitive arches and complex perspective vistas, convey a strong, almost claustrophobic, sense of confinement. 

   The following month, when Vincent was allowed outside the asylum walls and began to work in the surrounding countryside, his paintings achieved an astonishing sense of openness and energy. 
The large gallery dedicated to the landscapes done that summer is one of the high points of the exhibition. 
These paintings not only convey a vivid sense of the violent Provencal countryside, they are also charged with powerful human emotion. 
If impressionist landscapes can be characterized as depictions of nature seen through a temperament, van Gogh's landscapes are images of a temperament imposed upon nature. 
Yet at the same time that they give a powerful sense of the artist's highly emotional response to the world around him, they are also some of the most intelligently rendered landscapes in the history of art. 

   This quality of painterly intelligence is something that is often overlooked in discussions of van Gogh's work. 
Because of the mythology that has sprung up around his life -- the halting speech, the amputated ear, the fits of insanity leading to suicide -- poor Vincent is often considered a kind of awkward madman who flailed wildly at his canvases, maniacally brushing on thick gobs of brightly colored pigment. 
In fact, nothing could be further from the truth. 

   What is so impressive about his mature paintings, and especially about these landscapes, is how careful and restrained their intricate system of paint application is, and how sharply focused the powerful emotional feeling that it expresses. 

   Van Gogh disciplined his powerful emotions, in his paintings and in his drawings, with carefully thought out systems of rhythmic marks. 
The variations in the rhythm and direction of these marks, inflected by color and the thick paint surface, express the inner rhythms of the subject itself. 
In "Green Wheat Field," for example, the varying rhythms of the brush strokes evoke the wind in the wheat, the rolling hills, the roiling sky. 
In the numerous paintings of olive trees, the violently graphic forms of the twisted branches are echoed by the rolling hills behind them, which suggests natural struggle and growth, and even a supernatural vision. 

   This larger sense of things is nowhere better seen than in the famous "Starry Night." 
Here the blazing stars and spiraling sky are a truly cosmic vision, in relation to which the works and aspirations of man (represented by the village and church steeple) appear puny indeed. 
A similar exhilaration and transcendence is also evident in the Metropolitan Museum's sonorous "Cypresses," in which field, trees, mountain and sky all share the same stupendous rolling motion, and in the eerily romantic night scene, "Road With Cypress and Star," done shortly before van Gogh left for the north, in May 1890. 

   The paintings done in Auvers-sur-Oise, some 20 miles north of Paris, are filled with the more silvery, less violently colored light of the northern spring. 
Ever sensitive to his surroundings, van Gogh again painted the surrounding countryside as spring gave way to summer, and did some very impressive portraits. 

   Perhaps the most striking of these is the expressively distorted portrait of Dr. Gachet, whom Vincent's brother Theo had asked to look after the painter at Auvers. 
Van Gogh wrote Theo that he thought the man was "as ill and distraught as you or me." 
The picture conveys an extraordinary sense of anguished melancholy and of what van Gogh once called "the heartbroken expression of our time." 

   Among the most impressive pictures in the exhibition are the unusually elongated "double-square" landscapes that van Gogh did during his last days. 
The imagery of these paintings runs from near-abstraction to high drama. 
In "Roots and Tree Trunks," the fiercely angular forms that twist and push against each other are set ambiguously against a pulsing background that verges on pure abstraction. 
In the famous "Crows Over the Wheatfield," thought by some to be the artist's last painting, the dramatic flight of the crows over the wind-swept wheat conveys an urgent sense of threat that verges on allegory. 

   In these, as in so many other of van Gogh's paintings, our experience of the familiar is transformed into something quite unfamiliar, but nonetheless vividly recognizable. 
Perhaps it is this combination of the familiar and the strange that makes his paintings so popular with general audiences. 
They speak in a language simple enough to be understood by all but at the same time subtle and complex enough to give even the most sophisticated viewer much to ponder and marvel at. 

   Ronald Pickvance's catalog offers a wealth of fascinating biographical information as well as detailed discussion of the individual pictures, all of which are reproduced in color. 
The exhibition is sponsored by E.F. Hutton &amp; Co., the Florence J. Gould Foundation and the Robert Wood Johnson Jr. Charitable Trust. 

</TEXT>
