<HEAD>Paintings by Van Gogh, Cezanne Recovered After Theft</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds price sought for stolen paintings, additional details.
No pickup</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL VERSCHUUR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMSTERDAM, Netherlands (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police used an undercover agent
posing as a prospective buyer today to recover three 19th-century
masterpieces, including works by Vincent van Gogh and Paul Cezanne.
   All three paintings taken from Amsterdam's Municipal Museum last
month were recovered undamaged, according to police spokesman Klaas
Wilting.
   The paintings, valued at up to $52 million, were seized when
police raided a hotel and arrested a 36-year-old man who was
selling them for $1.14 million, Wilting said. The money was
confiscated during the raid at the Pullman Hotel, he said.
   The paintings are Van Gogh's 1888 ``Carnations,'' the 1894 still
life ``Bottle with Apples'' by Cezanne, and a work by Dutch painter
Johan Jongkind, ``The House of Maitre Billaud in Nevers,'' done in
1874.
   In their pre-dawn raid, police found the Van Gogh inside the
hotel and the two other paintings in a car parked outside, Wilting
said. The artworks were wrapped in blankets, Wilting said.
   Another police spokesman, Joost van Wijngaarden, said an
undercover police officer had posed as a buyer in the deal, but he
refused to give details.
   Two other people, thought to be genuine prospective buyers, also
were arrested, police said earlier. All suspects were being held
pending charges. None were identified, in line with Dutch police
practice.
   Police refused to say whether the undercover police officer was
posing as a partner of the other two prospective buyers, or whether
police had a role in raising the substantial amount of cash.
   There was no immediate word whether the alleged seller, who has
a police burglary record, was involved in the May 20 break-in and
theft at the Municipal Museum. In that incident, a ground-floor
window was smashed to gain access to the museum.
   Last week, police received anonymous tips that buyers for the
paintings were being solicited abroad, Wilting said.
   ``We got hard evidence of that early this week and that's when
we decided to act,'' said Wilting.
   Museum director Wim Beeren said when the paintings were stolen
that they are so famous it would be almost impossible to sell them
on the open market. He speculated they were stolen on commission by
a private collector.
   The three works were only insured for fire damage, but Beeren
said at the time the huge loss estimate was due in part to the
record prices paid for recently auctioned van Goghs.
   Last November, a collector paid $53 million for van Gogh's
``Irises'' at a New York auction and eight months earlier, the
artist's ``Sunflowers'' was auctioned in London for $29.8 million.
   However, experts at the Christie's auction firm in London said
soon after the Amsterdam burglary that the three paintings together
were worth just $11 million, with van Gogh's estimated at about $2
million. Experts at the Amsterdam museum put the value of the three
at up to $52 million.
   The smashed window in the May burglary at the Municipal Museum
triggered an electronic alarm at the museum's private security
firm, which reportedly took 20 minutes to warn police and
investigate the burglary.
   The museum holds about 3,200 mainly 19th and 20th-century
artworks, but has had no night guard since 1975, when
round-the-clock surveillance was abolished as an economy measure.
